properties.title: New Delhi Railway Station
Chocolateeee
delhi's snowfall.
Bihari workers. India
craggy
all for one, one for all
inscribed, subscribed
just lay
dawn sombre
the ball
flow
the bright and the opaque
bemused
untombed
in bloom
the mortification of a light
lattices
weathering
door to nowhere
pseudo sufi
pester
tall
and there
flight

properties.title: Red Fort in Delhi: The Symbol of India
properties.description: superbsunny007 posted a photo: Red Fort in Delhi: The Symbol of India Lal Quila also called the Red Fort is one of the most important monuments of India. It stands on the bank of river Yamuna. Lal Quila stands at the eastern side of Shahjahanabad and the very name of "Lal Quila" comes from the huge wall that encloses the whole structure. The wall is 2.5 km long and the height varies from 16 meters on the river side to 33 meters towards the city.One of the special attraction of the fort is the huge wall that encompasses the whole structure. The walls have two entrances, one at the delhi gate and the other at the Lahore gate. Lahore Gate is the main entrance point of the fort, leading to Chatta Chowk. It is a coveres bazaar street where merchnats sold their goods to the nobles of the court.

properties.title: Lotus Temple
properties.description: Sandeep K Bhat posted a photo: Bahá'í House of Worship, New Delhi, India. Inspired by the lotus flower, this structure is composed of 27 free-standing marble clad "petals" arranged in clusters of three to form nine sides. The nine doors of the Lotus Temple open onto a central hall slightly more than 40 meters tall that is capable of holding up to 2,500 people. Please see my flickr comment below for the color version. Best viewed large and on black www.flickr.com/photos/sandeepkbhat/4838750534/in/photostr...

properties.title: The Qutub
properties.description: NChoudhary posted a photo: The Qutub Minar is a tower located in Delhi, India. It is the world's tallest brick minaret with a height of 72.5 meters (237.8 ft). The Qutub Minar is notable for being one of the earliest and most prominent examples of Indo-Islamic architecture. It is surrounded by several other ancient and medieval structures and ruins, collectively known as Qutub complex.

properties.title: Questionable wiring
properties.description: HousingRevolution.org posted a photo: This is the electrical wiring on the outside of an apartment building in one of New Delhi's more upscale, wealthy neighborhoods. So you can imagine what the wiring is like in the poorer neighborhoods

properties.title: More waste
properties.description: HousingRevolution.org posted a photo: The building isn't even finished yet, and look how much is going to waste. The workers on the ground usually throw the bricks up to the workers on the next floor up. Sometimes they miss.

properties.title: Waste
properties.description: HousingRevolution.org posted a photo: The building isn't even finished yet, and look how much is going to waste!

properties.title: Watch your step!
properties.description: HousingRevolution.org posted a photo: A staircase in decay in an apartment building in one of New Delhi's wealthier neighborhoods. Who can tell us what causes this kind of deterioration?

properties.title: Questionable brickwork
properties.description: HousingRevolution.org posted a photo: I'm not a brickmason, but I can still look at this wall and see several things that could be improved. (What do you see?) This is part of a apartment building currently under construction in one of New Delhi's more upscale, wealthy neighborhoods. The holes in the wall are for bamboo poles, which the construction workers use to support platforms for building higher.

properties.title: Unreinforced walls
properties.description: HousingRevolution.org posted a photo: The concrete sections of this building under construction (in one of New Delhi's wealthier neighborhoods) are reinforced with steel rebar. But the brick walls (the thickness of the length of one brick) are completely unreinforced. They'll later be covered with cement. This design provides very poor insulation from heat. And what about its seismic safety?
